 Thomas Graves, Jr.\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1970|02|03}}\n| birth_place   = [[St. Petersburg, Florida|St. Petersburg]], [[Florida]]\n| death_date    =\n| death_place   =\n| party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| otherparty    =\n| relations     =\n| spouse        = Julie Howard Graves\n| children      = JoAnn, John T. III, and Janey\n| residence     = [[Ranger, Georgia]]\n| alma_mater    = [[University of Georgia]]\n| occupation    =\n| religion      = [[Southern Baptist]]\n| signature     =\n| website       =\n| footnotes     =\n| branch =\n| serviceyears =\n| rank =\n| unit =\n| commands =\n| awards =\n}}\n\n'''John Thomas''' \"'''Tom'''\" '''Graves, Jr.''' (born February 3, 1970) is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|GA|14}}, serving since winning a special election for {{ushr|GA|9}} in 2010. He is a member of the [[United States Republican Party|Republican Party]].  Graves served in the [[Georgia House of Representatives]] before being elected to the House of Representatives.\n\n== Early life, education, and business career ==\nTom Graves was born in [[St. Petersburg, Florida]] on February 3, 1970.<ref name=\"WSJ12\">{{cite news |title=Tom Graves: Winner |author= |url=http://projects.wsj.com/campaign2012/candidates/view/tom-graves--GA-H |work=Wall Street Journal |date=2012 |accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> He graduated from [[Cass High School (Georgia)|Cass High School]] of [[Cartersville, GA]], where he played linebacker and offensive guard on the school football team.<ref name=\"Ranger\">{{cite news |title=Ranger\u2019s most unlikely politician Tom Graves reflects on his first year in Congress |author=Karissa Stewart |url=http://www.northwestgeorgianews.com/archive/ranger-s-most-unlikely-politician-tom-graves-reflects-on-his/article_5fee3563-f697-5e33-9392-0df3f73a3897.html?mode=story |work=Northwest Georgia News |date=27 April 2011 |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> Graves earned his [[Bachelor of Business Administration]] from the [[University of Georgia]]. After college, he bought a landscaping company before working in real estate investment.<ref name=Ranger/> Graves lives in [[Ranger, Georgia]], southeast of [[Dalton, Georgia|Dalton]].<ref name=WSJ12/>\n\nIn 2007, Graves and former Georgia Senate Majority Leader [[Chip Rogers]] took out a loan from Bartow County Bank to purchase and renovate a motel in Calhoun. In 2011, it was reported that Bartow County Bank had sued Rogers and Graves for defaulting on their $2.2 million bank loan. They countersued the bank in response.<ref name=Sheinin11>{{cite news |title=Attorney for Graves, Rogers: Bank is at Fault |author=Aaron Gould Sheinin |url=http://www.ajc.com/news/news/local/attorney-for-graves-rogers-bank-is-at-fault/nQKbg/ |work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution |date=11 August 2011 |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref><ref name=Redmon11>{{cite news|title=Attorneys for Graves, Rogers, bank refuse to disclose settlement details|url=http://www.ajc.com/news/georgia-politics-elections/attorneys-for-graves-rogers-1097719.html|accessdate=October 6, 2011|newspaper=The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|date=August 11, 2011|author=Jeremy Redmon|author2=Aaron Gould Sheinin}}</ref> In August 2011, both parties dismissed their claims before going to hearing, settling the dispute out of court, and no details of the settlement were disclosed.<ref name=Redmon11/><ref>{{cite news|title=UPDATE: Lawsuit against Graves dismissed|url=http://www.calhountimes.com/view/full_story/15037019/article-UPDATE--Lawsuit-against-Graves-dismissed-?|accessdate=October 7, 2011|newspaper=The Calhoun Times|date=August 12, 2011|author=Rachel Goff}}</ref> Following the settlement, the former chairman for Bartow County Bank said that the default on Graves and Rogers' loan had \"contributed significantly\" to the bank's financial collapse earlier that year.<ref>{{cite news|title=Former bank chair: Tich loan complications contributed to bank collapse|url=http://www.calhountimes.com/view/full_story/15255696/article-Former-bank-chair--Tich-loan--complications-contributed-to-bank-collapse?|accessdate=October 6, 2011|newspaper=Calhoun Times|date=August 31, 2011}}</ref> Graves received criticism in ''[[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution]]'' on the grounds that the outcome of this business venture appeared to some individuals to undermine his stated commitment to fiscal responsibility.<ref name=AJC12>{{cite news |title=In failed hotel venture, Ga. Republicans appear to cut loan nearly in half |author= |url=http://www.ajc.com/news/news/local/in-failed-hotel-venture-ga-republicans-appear-to-c/nQSYD/ |work=Atlanta Journal-Constitution |date=27 March 2012 |accessdate=18 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Georgia House of Representatives ==\n\n===Elections===\nTom E. Shanahan retired as Representative to Georgia's 10th District in 2002, and Graves won as his successor with 60 percent of the vote.<ref name=Ourcampaign1>{{cite web |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=49518 |title=GA State House 010 |author= |date= |work=Our Campaigns |publisher= |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> Graves later ran, unopposed, to serve as House Representative to Georgia's 12th district in 2004.<ref name=Ourcampaign2>{{cite web |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=141356 |title=GA State House 012 |author= |date= |work=Our Campaigns |publisher= |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> He was re-elected, after two races in which he ran against primary challenger Bill Pickett in 2006<ref name=Ourcampaign3>{{cite web |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=288565 |title=GA State House 012 |author= |date= |work=Our Campaigns |publisher= |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> and unopposed in 2008.<ref name=Ourcampaign4>{{cite web |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=464215 |title=GA State House 012 |author= |date= |work=Our Campaigns |publisher= |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nGraves served on the Transportation, Ways and Means committee and on the Health and Human services committee during his tenure in the Georgia House of Representatives.<ref name=Calhoun07>{{cite news |title=Rep. Graves gets appointment as 'Hawk' in House |author= |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=375&dat=20070127&id=KAQvAAAAIBAJ&sjid=UjkDAAAAIBAJ&pg=2906,3008249 |work=Calhoun Times |date=27 January 2007 |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> He also served as Vice Chairman on the Motor Vehicles committee.<ref name=Schow11>{{cite web |url=http://heritageaction.com/2011/12/congressional-profile-rep-tom-graves-r-ga/ |title=CONGRESSIONAL PROFILE: REP. TOM GRAVES (R-GA) |author=Ashe Schow |date=6 December 2011 |work=Congressional Profile |publisher=Heritage Action for America |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\nAs a member of the Georgia House, Graves supported legislation to provide tax cuts and tax credits,<ref name=BizJournal10>{{cite news |title=Georgia's political leaders react to SOTU |author= |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/stories/2010/01/25/daily63.html?page=all |work=Atlanta Business Chronicle |date=25 January 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=Karkaria10>{{cite news |title=Tax credits sought for startups, jobs |author=Urvaksh Karkaria |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/atlanta/stories/2010/02/08/story5.html?page=all |work=Atlanta Business Chronicle |date=8 February 2010 |accessdate=6 May 2015}}</ref> including introducing the Jobs, Opportunity and Business Success (JOBS) Act of 2009.<ref name=CTimes10>{{cite news |title=Graves to announce JOBS Act today |author= |url=http://www.northwestgeorgianews.com/calhoun_times/news/graves-to-announce-jobs-act-today/article_d31dc354-8474-5685-b618-313f6c1c5607.html |work=The Calhoun Times |date=27 January 2010 |accessdate=4 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=Speagle10>{{cite news |title=Lawmakers to look at boosting jobs |author=Ashley Speagle |url=http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/news/story/2010/jan/24/lawmakers-to-look-at-boosting-jobs/2967/ |work=The Times Free Press |date=24 January 2010 |accessdate=4 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nGraves was named Legislator of the Year in 2009 by the [[American Legislative Exchange Council]].<ref name=SouthernStudies>{{cite web |url=http://www.southernstudies.org/2012/05/the-souths-alec-all-stars.html |title=The South's ALEC All-Stars |author=Chris Kromm |date=1 May 2012 |work=Facing South |publisher=Institute for Southern Studies |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> Later that year, he was awarded the Guardian of Small Business award by the [[National Federation of Independent Business]].<ref name=Bodnar12>{{cite news |title=Freedomworks Endorses Tom Graves for Republican Study Committee Chairman |author=Jacqueline Bodnar |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-308233037.html |work=States News Service |date=12 November 2012 |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n== U.S. House of Representatives ==\n\n=== Elections ===\n\n====2010====\nIn May 2010, Graves won a special election to replace Republican US House Representative [[Nathan Deal]].<ref name=Espo10>{{cite news |title=Politics; Narrow defeats, stunning victories |author=David Espo |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-22172447.html |work=Charlestown Gazette |date=9 June 2010 |accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> On June 8, 2010, Graves won the run-off for the special election against former state Senator [[Lee Hawkins]].<ref name=GeorgiaJun10>{{cite web |url=http://sos.ga.gov/elections/election_results/2010_0608/swall.htm |title=Georgia Election Results |author= |date=8 June 2010 |work= |publisher=State of Georgia |accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> Graves then faced Hawkins two more times, in another primary election and run off before winning the November 2, 2010 general election unopposed.<ref name=Kurtzleben10>{{cite news |title=Graves and Hawkins Face off in Georgia Primary |author=Danielle Kurtzleben |url=http://www.usnews.com/news/articles/2010/08/10/graves-and-hawkins-face-off-in-georgia-primary |work=US News |date=10 August 2010 |accessdate=8 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=Georgia10>{{cite web |url=http://sos.ga.gov/elections/election_results/2010_1102/00309.htm |title=Election Results |author= |date=2 November 2010 |work= |publisher=State of Georgia |accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> Upon his election, Graves joined the House Republican Whip team,<ref name=Peterson14>{{cite news |title=Kevin McCarthy Enlists Conservative Graves for Nomination Speech |author=Kristina Peterson |url=http://blogs.wsj.com/washwire/2014/06/19/kevin-mccarthy-enlists-conservative-graves-for-nomination-speech/ |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=19 June 2014 |accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> which he later left in 2011.<ref name=Cogan11>{{cite news |title=Tom Graves: A rising house star or big headache? |author1=Marin Cogan |author2=John Bresnahan |url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/1011/66209.html |work=Politico.com |date=17 October 2011 |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> In January 2013, Graves rejoined the Whip team, and is a member as of 2014.<ref name=Peterson14/>\n\n====2012====\nGraves\u2019 home in [[Ranger, Georgia|Ranger]] was drawn into the newly created 14th district\u2014essentially, the northwestern portion of his old district\u2014during the 2012 census.  He opted to run for reelection in the newly created district.<ref name=AssociatedPress12>{{cite news |title=US Rep. Graves advances in 14th District primary |author= |url=http://timesfreepress.com/news/2012/jul/31/us-rep-graves-advances-14th-district-primary/?print |work=Associated Press |date=31 July 2012 |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> The 14th was no less Republican than the 9th, and Graves won the November 6, 2012 election against Democratic challenger Daniel \u201cDanny\u201d Grant with 73 percent of the vote.<ref name=NBC12>{{cite web |url=http://elections.nbcnews.com/ns/politics/2012/georgia/house/14/#.VFulpfTF9LM |title=Georgia Congressional District 14 election results |author= |date=7 November 2012 |work= |publisher= |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== Tenure ===\nGraves is a [[pro-life]] politician and voted in 2011 to limit funding to [[Planned Parenthood]].<ref name=\"InsideCongress\">{{cite web |url=http://politics.nytimes.com/congress/votes/112/house/1/93 |title=Inside Congress |author= |date=19 February 2011 |work= |publisher= |accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref>  He has stated that he opposes abortion \"without exception\", including when the mother's life is at stake.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nationaljournal.com|title=National Journal|work=nationaljournal.com}}</ref> In 2013, Graves voted in support of a bill which allowed abortions after 20 weeks post-fertilization if a mother's life is endangered, or if conception occurred through rape or incest.<ref name=Rodgers13>{{cite news |title= U.S. House Passes Bill to Protect Unborn in Sixth Month and Later; National Right to Life Commends Seven Georgia Lawmakers |author=Jessica Rodgers |url=http://www.christiannewswire.com/news/8865172295.html |work=Christian Newswire |date=18 June 2013 |accessdate=18 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nGraves was endorsed by the Atlanta [[Tea Party movement|Tea Party]] in 2010.<ref name=\"Reed10\">{{cite news |title=The Year of the (Conservative) Woman |author=Ralph Reed |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-232200734.html |work=Faith and Freedom Coalition |date=9 June 2010 |accessdate=5 November 2014}}</ref> He authored the Defund Obamacare Act in 2010 and reintroduced the bill in the 112th and 113th Congress.<ref name=\"Alberta13\">{{cite news |title=The Man Behind the Campaign to Defund Obamacare |author=Tim Alberta |url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/daily/the-man-behind-the-campaign-to-defund-obamacare-20131105 |work=National Journal |date=5 November 2013 |accessdate=11 December 2014}}</ref>\n\nGraves co-sponsored a [[Balanced budget amendment|balanced-budget amendment]] in both the 112th and 113th Congresses and supported the [[Cut, Cap and Balance Act]] of 2011, which aimed to reduce federal spending and establish caps in future spending.<ref name=\"Cogan11\"/> The same year, Graves introduced the HOME Act to allow Americans to make withdrawals from their retirement accounts to pay timely mortgage payments in 2011.<ref name=\"Isakson11\">{{cite press release |title=SEN. ISAKSON, REP. GRAVES INTRODUCE THE HOME ACT TO HELP AMERICANS KEEP THEIR HOMES |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2478281171.html |publisher=US Federal News Service |date=7 October 2011 |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> He also voted against removing US troops from Afghanistan in March 2011.<ref name=\"Issues\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ontheissues.org/GA/Tom_Graves.htm |title=Tom Graves |author= |date= |work= |publisher=On The Issues |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> Graves introduced the Transportation Empowerment Act (TEA) in 2011, meant to lower the federal gas tax to 3.7 cents per gallon and transfer nearly all funding authority to U.S. states over a period of five years.<ref name=\"HeritageAction1\">{{cite news |title=TOM GRAVES: TEA ACT MEANS BETTER ROADS WITHOUT RAISING TAXES |author=Katherine Rosario |url=http://heritageaction.com/2014/02/tom-graves-tea-act-means-better-roads-without-raising-taxes/ |work=Heritage Action for America |date=20 February 2014 |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref>\nGraves voted in favor of the [[Water Resources Reform and Development Act of 2013|Water Resources Reform and Development Act]] in 2013, which funded the Savannah Harbor Expansion Project<ref name=\"Water\">{{cite web |url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/votes/113-2013/h560 |title=Water Resources and Reform Act |author= |date=23 August 2014 |work=govtrack.us |publisher= |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> in its expansion of the Savannah Harbor shipping channel from a depth of \u221242 feet to \u221247 feet.<ref name=\"USArmy\">{{cite web |url=http://www.sas.usace.army.mil/Missions/CivilWorks/SavannahHarborExpansion.aspx |title=Savannah Harbor Expansion Project |author= |date= |work= |publisher=US Army Corps of Engineers |accessdate=11 November 2014}}</ref> He also authored the [[Email Privacy Act]] with Representatives [[Kevin Yoder]] and [[Jared Polis]].<ref name=\"Polis13\">{{cite press release |title=Polis, Yoder Bipartisan Email Privacy Amendment Unanimously Adopted in Committee Amendment Ensures 4th Amendment Protections Cover Emails |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-337194754.html |publisher= |date=18 July 2013 |accessdate=6 November 2014}}</ref> Graves led the national movement to defund the [[Patient Protection and Affordable Care Act]] (\"Obamacare\") in 2013.<ref name=Alberta13/>\n\n=== Committee assignments ===\nGraves is a member of the [[United States House Committee on Appropriations]]. In 2014, he was selected to serve as chairman of the [[United States House Appropriations Subcommittee on the Legislative Branch|Subcommittee on the Legislative Branch]] for the 114th Congress.<ref name=Percy15>{{cite news |title=Political notes: February 2015 |author=Susan Percy |url=http://www.georgiatrend.com/February-2015/Political-Notes-February-2015/ |work=Georgia Trend |date=February 2015 |accessdate=13 March 2015}}</ref> His membership also includes the subcommittees on Defense and Financial Services and General Government.<ref name=Malloy15>{{cite news |title=Tom Graves scores spot on defense spending panel |author=Daniel Malloy |url=http://politics.blog.ajc.com/2015/01/15/tom-graves-scores-spot-on-defense-spending-panel/ |work=AJC |date=15 January 2015 |accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=Defense>{{cite web |url=http://appropriations.house.gov/about/members/defense.htm |title=Defense Subcommittee |author= |date= |work= |publisher= |accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Caucus memberships===\nGraves is a member of the [[Caucuses of the United States Congress#C|House Congressional Chicken Caucus]], the House General Aviation Caucus, the [[Caucuses of the United States Congress#C|Joint Congressional Sportsmen's Caucus]], the House Congressional Balanced Budget Amendment Caucus, the House [[Republican Study Committee]] and the House Congressional Diabetes Caucus.<ref name=VOP>{{cite web |url=http://www.voicesforvinyl.uschamberpartners.com/voter-resources/official/211906/Tom/Graves |title=US Rep Tom Graves Profile |author= |date= |work=Voices for Vinyl Legislative Action Center |publisher= |accessdate=12 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\nGraves and his wife Julie, a schoolteacher, have three children, and are active members of Belmont Baptist Church in [[Calhoun, Georgia]].<ref name=Baptist>{{cite news|last=Staff|first=|title=Ten Southern Baptists sworn in as new reps.|url=http://www.bpnews.net/bpnews.asp?id=34378|accessdate=25 December 2014|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141226010629/http://www.bpnews.net/34378|archivedate=December 26, 2014 |newspaper=Baptist Press|date=5 January 2011}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://tomgraves.house.gov/ Congressman Tom Graves] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.gravesforcongress.org/ Tom Graves for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Georgia/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Tom_Graves_%5BR-14%5D|Tom Graves}}\n{{CongLinks | congbio = G000560 | ballot = Tom_Graves | nndb = 248/000235540 | votesmart = 31969 | govtrack = 412388| opencong = 412388 | rollcall = 31434 | politifact = tom-graves | fec = H0GA09030 | opensecrets = N00030788 | assets = tom-graves | legistorm = 2721/Rep_Tom_Graves_GA.html | followthemoney = 4743 | ontheissues = GA/Tom_Graves.htm | congress = tom-graves/1979 | worldcat = | cspan = 11519 | imdb = 4649112 | bloomberg = | nyt = | washpo = gIQA82YuKP }}\n* {{C-SPAN|11519}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state = Georgia\n| district = 9\n| before= [[Nathan Deal]]\n| after=[[Doug Collins (politician)|Doug Collins]]\n| years= June 14